rComments: He looks annoyed when students are commenting, part of why i didnt speak in this class. Imagine youre already speaking in front of hundreds of people and then getting discouraging looks from the prof while youre talking, feel bad for ppl who did, dont know what he wants to hear
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Beware of pop quizzes']

rComments: Professor Lee was an amazing prof and did an excellent job leading discussions and allowing everyone to have their own opinions on controversial topics. He was VERY easy to approach about any help you may need. He was TRULY an inspiration and brought back a passion to learn that I thought I had lost at U of T. Thank you Professor Lee!

Best soc prof at UofT hands down. Facilitates thought provoking class discussion but it's optional to participate. Took both serial homicide class and hip hop. Found serial homicide course more interesting but each were well rounded in their own respect. Note that in both classes I took with him used tophat, wish I had known when I started.

the best professor i had in all my years at U of T. the most interesting class, i wish i met him earlier in my studies i would take all of Dr Lee's classes! I tell all my friends about his class. his teaching style is just awesome
Good professor who teaches interesting courses. Takes a while to answer emails though

Good Prof... instructions for his assignments could be clear. Often gives very broad research topics and expects students to have a well-written essay. That being said his testing material is far better than his assignments.

Prof Lee is very caring and wants his students to succeed. That said, he expect top-notch writing, but he's always willing to help his students. He does an excellent job at making both the content and delivery of his lectures engaging and fascinating.
Joo Young is a boss. Took ASA400 and SOC396 with him. Fair marker, great lecturer and incredibly interesting topics and reading materials. Would recommend taking any courses he teaches at U of T.
Amazing Prof!! Must Take before leaving uoft. Sociology of Hip Hop was one of my fav courses, he was a really good prof, lectures were very interesting and eye-opening.

Prof Lee is chill af yet clearly cares/has high expectations for students. Put in the work and you'll get what you want (ie a good grade). Clear expectations. Entertaining lectures. A respectably small class size (a UofT first for me), and with this comes opportunities to grow as a student. Highly recommend the course if you're prepared to work.
Prof. Lee was an amazing professor and was really inspiring. I strongly recommend taking any course that he teaches, you will not be dissapointed!
The materials are super interesting, love his lecture style plus he is cute. Definitely recommend taking this class.

Best prof I've ever had. Seriously an inspiration. I'm actually sad I'm graduating this year because I won't get to take any of his classes anymore. He's an amazing guy, extremely fair professor, and hes gorgeous FYI. No one should graduate uoft without taking one of his classes. I inspire to be a prof just because of prof lee. Love you Jooyoung

One of the best profs at UofT. The type of professor who actually cares about his students. His tests are fair, class is very engaging and he is one of the coolest person you will ever meet. TAKE HIS CLASS!

Amazing prof and even better course. My project was to go to a bar, hang out with musicians and write about it. If you do the easy and fun weekly fieldwork, you can get 90+ in this class. Lee uses live Skype interviews with sociologists and class discussion. One of the best courses I've taken, and one of the best profs as well.

Coolest guy. If you come to class and do the work he is more than fair in marking. Has pop quiz's worth a sizeable chunk of mark so easy marks there. Seems to have same TA in most classes he teaches. Great course, really interesting.

Easily one of the three best profs I had at UTor. He's a former pop-and-locker. If you do the work and contribute to discussions, he will mark generously. The Bourgois text and ethnography readings are enjoyable. His enthusiasm for the sociology of hip-hop culture was infectious, and made for a good starting point to exploring qualitative analysis.
